tree.data: I was born March 10, 1915 to Anna (Esther) and Herman (Harris) Ness. From various stories told by other immigrants coming to the U.S., there seems to be a lot of misunderstanding of family names. So all of the above were observed

by the time I arrived. My father said that “Ness” was the right name, and my mother said that her maiden name was Feld.  I know nothing about her family, and never heard of siblings during my lifetime…although I know there were pa

ckages of clothing and other stuff sent regularly to the family in Austria. Bear in mind that I was born 7 years after Mack, the youngest of the family until I came along, and so there was probably lots of history that I missed. T

he story goes that my mother was 16 years old, and at that time this was considered “old maid” territory. My father, vagabonding around Europe from Russia, landed in this little farming town where Anna lived with her family.   Thi
s was followed immediately by the birth of Paul (Saul), followed soon thereafter by a daughter, Cecile.

This turn of events was more than Herman could handle, since he was fifteen years older than Anna.  He discovered that this life was not what he had in mind, and got in touch with his half-brother…who had migrated to America and w

as living in lrvington, NJ., with his wife and three children. Soon after this exchange of information, arrangements were apparently (and secretly) made, and Herman was off to America with no goodbyes. I assume there was an interv

al where he got a job, as he lived with this family for awhile. Meantime, I was given to understand, Anna put out a search for her husband, and shortly after, leaving the two children with her parents, met up with Herman at Ellis
Island (where all immigrants landed and were processed). A few years later, there was a trip back to Austria to get the children, and they were brought back to the U.S. to live as a family.

There is a large blank covering the next 7 years.  I was told that the kids went to school until they were considered old enough to work, and they helped Herman with his horse and wagon, going around neighborhoods selling fresh fr
uit and vegetables. The marriage was blessed with two more children, Sam (Sanford)....and Mack. Everyone worked, and Paul as the eldest, dropped out of school without finishing the 8th grade.

The marriage which seemed to be an off and on again affair, but finally broke up when they joined the work force.  Cecile left home at a very young age, and found work elsewhere.  I heard of an opportunity that Paul took with some

man who was interested in the newest form of transportation…the automobile and he wanted Paul to go with him to Detroit to seek his fortune there. Being the breadwinner, of course he was not allowed to go, and I always wondered w
hat would have happened if he had gotten in on the ground floor of the automobile explosion that happened then.

Anna added to the family fortunes by selling fruit baskets and delivering them as farewell gifts on cruise ships. Somewhere along the way, she became interested in real estate, and bought and sold on a small scale. She lived with

her four children and everyone worked. When she found a deal she couldn’t turn down, and did not have the money to complete it, she invited Herman back into the fold, took the money and shortly thereafter invited him to leave agai
n...this was the final breakup. One other result of this unfortunate reunion was another blessed event...me. I doubt that this was a period of great joy for the family. I was oblivious....

I grew up as an only child, since the rest of my siblings were either in school or working.  A man I never met came along when I was about 6 years old, who had a great impact on all of us. His name was Mr. Schulstadt, and he got i
n on the beginning of the cement garden

furniture business. I always thought my mother met him first, and he and Paul and my mother and Sam wound up in that business. It took off, and at one time, the top floor of Hahne’s department store in Newark was a showplace for c

ement flower pots, benches, gazing globes, etc. Things were better financially, and Paul became interested in coupling his garden furniture business with landscaping. This too did well.  [Note: from this point on, I can tell you w
hat I saw and lived with in our family.  The preceding was all second-hand.]

At this time, Paul found the farm in Watchung, which he bought with his own money, some of my mother’s, and some of my father’s as well. Anyway, it was run as a dairy farm.  The cows were already there, along with a sexy bull, som

e leg-horn chickens, and some guinea hens, ducks and geese.  Also, around this time, another man came along…Mr. Vis.  He knew all about growing plants, and quickly thereafter, greenhouses were erected on the farm, and the landscap

ing business became big time! Paul also kept the garden furniture place in Maplewood, with Sam turning out the orders, and Olive (the secretary in the office) turning out the bills. A very important member of this business was Bil
l, a huge, black man who supervised all the jobs that Paul contracted for.

After the farm came into existence, Paul did two things immediately....he caught chicken pox from me and was sick as a dog, and married Henrietta Rapp. My life became almost a normal one with this latest change of affairs, and Ett
a became the only mother I ever knew.  I loved her dearly! A few years later, Gloria was born, named for Gloria Swanson, as were many other children born at that time.

As my life was getting on (I was now out of high school), I left home and the farm…and never looked back. I did, however keep up my relationship with Paul, Etta, and Gloria.  Their house on the road was as far as I went on the far

m property.  [Note: If you are gathering the feeling by now that I had no relationship with my Mother or Sam or Max, you are correct. I didn’t know them as a child, or as an adult. My sister, being so much older, was on the fringe

s of my life, but she was good to me in many ways.]  Paul stayed on the farm. Sam and Paul had some kind of “difference” regarding the garden furniture business, so Sam then went into the laundry business.  He did well, made a lot

of money, and bought a lot of land.   Sam left his estate to Mack when he died some years ago.  [Note: I have always suspected that he and Mack were gay, and so this made some sense].  Cecile died living with friends in Virginia
after her husband died. Gloria went on to get married, had Doug and Jeff, and now you are all updated…and should have now have a clear understanding of how I got to like alcohol so much.

He was the oldest, born on the border of Austria and Poland to Anna Feld and Herman (Harris) Ness.  Anna was sixteen, Herman was thirty two. He was followed a couple of years later by Cecile. And a couple of years after this, life

changed for everyone, including us. Herman had come to a decision that married life was not for him, and he saved enough money to buy a ticket to America, where his half-brother already lived in Irvington, N.J., with his wife and
three children. I have no knowledge of that period of his life, except that there were some ugly rumors about him and his sister-in-law, with whom he lived at the time.

The next move came from my mother, who hired a private detective to find her husband, and she promptly came over to explain the situation to him. They lived together in marriage, and returned to bring Paul and Cecile to live with
them in the U.S. A few years later, Sam was born, followed by Mack two years after that.

My father worked at selling fruit and vegetables from a wagon, pulled by a horse...in those days, there were no supermarkets. The boys grew bigger daily, and when Paul got to about fourteen years, he found himself the head of the

family, my mother having removed my father from the home. Paul got a job with a man who hired him to work on automobiles, since he seemed to have mechanical abilities, and after some years, he offered to take Paul with him to Detr

oit (where he was headed to enter the new world of transportation). My mother didn’t see this as the way to go, and she had already started a business of her own supplying gift baskets to departing cruise passengers. She also met

a man whose last name was Shulstadt, who made cement garden benches, lions for front steps, flower pots, etc.  Paul joined him and that was the beginning of his career in producing a line of garden furniture. It became quite a cra

ze, and at one point, his products took over a whole floor of Hahne’s department store, in downtown Newark, which was the shopping center for the area at the time.  His business really thrived. He had a partnership with Sam, who w

as old enough now to join him....neither a graduate from primary school.  He then started doing some landscaping and lawn-cutting, assembling a small crew to do this. From there he became interested more in landscaping, and had an
innate ability to create artistic gardens. He took some courses at Rutgers College, and branched out seriously in the landscaping field, and again his business thrived.

Paul also became very good at buying low, and selling high, various properties, like the Short Hills Mall, and King’s market in Millburn (which was a golf driving range…whereas he first saw it as an opportunity. At this point, he
courted Henrietta Rapp, who was a friend of Adolf and Eva…who had a delicatessen across the street from the shop his business (on Springfield Avenue in Maplewood).

Since things were going along pretty well, Paul decided it was time to look for a place to grow his own plants for use in his landscaping jobs. Accordingly, he found a dairy farm in Watchung that he liked.  While the real estate m

arket at that time was very high, he mortgaged everything up to the hilt, moved the family into the house in back of the farm, married Henrietta…and also moved into the house in the front of the farm, on Mountain Blvd. The marriag
e ceremony was delayed because he caught chicken pox from me. I recovered quickly, he

didn’t...but all’s well that ends well. And if I had to pick the one significant thing that happened to make the biggest difference in my life, it was having Etta as my sister-in-law as I was growing up. She was the mother I never
had, and I could never repay her for her love and kindness.’

Things were fine until that day in 1929 when the stock market…and our world…fell apart. The mortgage payments went on, and Paul’s business paid them, but it was tough going.  While we had tons of food (living on a farm), there was

no cash. Gloria was born then, and I was her first baby-sitter. Life on the farm was equal parts good/bad, and as I was now all of seventeen, I couldn’t wait to get to the big city to begin my life.  So right after high school, I

did…and never looked back. Paul had some difficulty at that time with Mack, and I never knew what it was about, but from then on the family was split....Mack stayed on the farm, Gloria grew up, and Paul/Etta/Gloria moved away fro

m the farm and ended up in Short Hills. Paul still did landscaping, as the cement business was over.  But he then started doing some real estate buying and selling, doing well. He worked to the end, but doing less and less, and hi

s vacations were spent with Ralph and me at our house down on Long Beach Island, and in Florida in the winter. His health became compromised, but not to where he was limited in his activities. Henrietta developed cancer and she pa

ssed away quietly, pretty much as she had lived her life. Paul had a final heart attack in Florida and passed away not so quietly. When Gloria and I went to see him, he wanted us to remove his restraints, since he resented them.

Of course we couldn’t, whereupon he looked up at me and said.....”l thought I could depend on you, but now I see you are as crazy as the rest of these people here. I laughed then, and now as I remember it, knowing that he didn’t m

There are two heroes in our family. Because both of them acted heroically, we are where we are, and I can sagely say that if my father did not make the journey in the first place, none of us would be here. And Paul pulled this fam

ily through good and bad times.  We have all benefited from his generosity and love, and I still miss him and those great arguments we used to so enjoy.  I loved him then, I love him still, and you should all be grateful to have h

My father was born Harris Nass in Russia, and by the time he got to America, his name was changed by the Immigration officials (to Herman Ness). He was in charge of the horses of the Russian Army, stationed where he lived. I don’t

know exactly what he did...he may have exercised them, trained them, treated them, but he never said. Apparently he decided to roam, left home as a young man, wandered through Europe and wound up meeting my mother Anna (who was b

orn in Austria on the German border...which at that time may have been in any one of the Balkan States, since it was all the Hungarian Empire then).  I guess there was some romance, followed by a marriage. She was 16 years old the

n, and her family thought Harris would be just right for her. They were married, and soon had Paul, while living with her family. Cecile came along a short time thereafter. However, it seems that Harris got the old urge to travel
again, and left for America with no forwarding address. His half brother Nat had gone the same route some years before, but took his wife with him.  So Herman moved in with this family.

He stayed long enough to hit on his hostess, Minna, and shortly thereafter he left (I imagine by invitation), and struck out on his own. Meanwhile, my mother’s family decided to find Herman, and so they sent Anna to America to exp
lain the situation to him. They settled in Newark and after a while, returned home to get Paul and Cecile.   Soon the family was established back in the U.S., and Sam and Mack were then added.

Herman went into business on his own with a horse and wagon, selling fruits and vegetables. Paul went to school when he didn’t have to help with the business.  However, when he got to the 8th grade, he quit school and started work
ing odd jobs. The first was with a man who was going to take him to Detroit to work on automobiles, which just came into use.

My mother had other ideas, and she refused to let him go, since she had decided she would do better without Herman, and they separated. A few years later, she needed some money, and Herman was asked to fill this need. I’m guessing

, but I think some promises were made with this transaction. I am the result of that short-lived reunion.  She bought a two-family house on Peshine Avenue, which was then a German neighborhood.  She also became an entrepreneur of

sorts, with a store that sold steamer-baskets of fruit and preserves, to be delivered to ships for passengers leaving for foreign ports. She became very interested in real estate too, and when Paul found the “dream” farm to turn i

nto a nursery, there was a shortage of money to complete the deal. My mother talked my father into turning over his savings of the many years that they were separated, and that made the whole thing possible. The farm was bought by
Paul and Anna Ness, and Herman was invited to leave again.  And did so, a lot more broke than when he arrived.

I never saw him until I was in high school and looked him up. He was working in a “chop shop” (although they had a different name for it then), and he took apart all kinds of autos and machines. He lived alone in various apartment

s until I got married and Ken was born. He came every single day to push Ken down to Weequahic Park at the end of the street, and patiently shook branches for his grandson to look at until he fell asleep.

When I moved to our first house in Millington, he came to live with me for a few years (I’ll tell you why when I tell the story about Ken). He left after awhile to live with my sister, and then he went to live in a retirement faci
lity where he had several heart attacks, and finally passed away there.

My memories of him include his giving me a flawed diamond he brought with him when he came to America. He heard that immigration officials sometimes took away money from the immigrants, and he figured a small stone would be overlo

oked and always worth something [Note: That became my engagement ring, then Denise’s, now Brooke’s.]  He also bought me a Dodge convertible...yellow...that he lovingly worked on to make it mechanically safe for me to drive when I

graduated high school.  He also lovingly put the hub-caps on wrong, so when I put air in the tires, they immediately fell off. I remember him as a generous man with a military bearing, who complained when he was 94 that he would h

ave lived longer if he hadn’t had such a hard life. I think he loved my mother to the end of HIS life....it was not returned, He was not a financially-responsible person, but he was gentle and I loved him.

He was the youngest of the original group, born in 1908…just a couple of years after Sam. He went to school longer the first three children, but never finished high school either. My memories of him begin with a few years in Newar

k, with my father gone from the family because my mother decided this was best for her. Paul and Sam worked. I was about 5, and saw Mack when he came home from school, a little later than me. My mother was part of the work group,

so she came home late at night with Paul and Sam. I have no memory of eating with the family, and I guess we were ahead of our time because we just grabbed something when we got hungry...whatever was around.  We didn’t have a food

pyramid of health to worry about then, and I loved white bread with condensed milk spread over it. Our home then was a two story house, where we lived on the top floor, on Peshine Avenue, which was pretty much a German area at th
at time, with a few Jewish shopkeepers.

Now Paul’s dream of a nursery became an obsession with him, and when he found 67 acres of a dairy farm, he mortgaged his business and God knows how many loans he took out to buy it. It was pretty exciting news for me, since I was

expecting to have my own pet calf to sleep with, Of course it didn’t happen. Mack dropped out of school and took over the running of the farm, along with my mother. To the best of my knowledge, he had no particular skills.  But I’

d learn to plant crops for sale, collect milk for the co-op milk company, drove a tractor and in general, took care of the animals. For a short while, Mack learned to play the violin, and I did too, thanks to my father who felt we
needed some musical education. Neither of us got very good at it, and I gave it up first. I continued to go to school, walking 2 miles each way to the schoolhouse down at the center of Watchung.

As we grew up, it was decided that Mack would stay on the farm.  And as we left our separate ways, when then WW2 came along, there was concern that if he left the farm, there would be no one to take the responsibility for my mothe
r. Accordingly, I am not sure of this, but it might have been done legally, giving him the ownership of the farm for the duration of the war. And that’s how it worked out, to his benefit.

He was built much like my father, had dark brown hair and bright blue eyes, about 5’ 9”, thin, and a loner. He read prodigiously and never dated anyone. When I was a student nurse at Muhlenberg Hospital, I once brought a fellow st

udent up for a weekend, and introduced them and they got along O.K. I guess, because I didn’t see much of either one of them. The only other time that I heard of him spending any time with a woman was when he allowed a trailer to

park on the farm, filled with prostitutes, and that only lasted for a few months. Whether or not he used their services, I have no idea....as that was years after I left the farm, and was married. His only contact with a female wa

s either a cow, or one of his pet sheep. His life was always as a lonely person. In later years, he seemed to make friends with a young man living and renting on the farm, who became the executor of his estate. My feeling is that
between this person, brother Sam, and that pet goat, he had lined up all the sexual activities that were necessary for him.

To the best of my knowledge, he never had any use for the family, except my mother and Sam......and never did one thing for any of us either. When my sister became a widow and just wanted a place to stay on the farm (in one of the

inelegant apartments he made out of the packing house), in spite of the entreaties by me and Gloria, he refused to do this, and refused to speak to any of us. All this time we were happily, and ignorantly, assuming that when he d

ied, those living would benefit because it was really Paul’s farm in the first place. He was neither happy nor ignorant, and proceeded with legal maneuvers to tie up ownership of the farm by virtue of living on it. From here I gue
ss you know the rest of the story of leaving the farm in his will to a Jewish charity, who promptly sold it to the town of Watchung, and I hear it is going to be a park.

When I first heard that Mack had a fatal heart attack, I was strongly tempted to attend the funeral to be sure he was rally dead, but it didn’t work out and now it doesn’t matter.  If you have gathered from my description of him t

hat I disliked him, you would be half-way right. I loathed and detested him and the ground he walked on. I won’t continue with this because I don’t want to use crude language on that piece of shit......

Farmer Mack Ness, who passed away in January 2004, named Jewish Federation of Central New Jersey as the sole beneficiary of his massive estate – provided the money be used to help Israel and a memorial be created to honor his moth
